I wish I had the article, but I saw that harm was going to be potentially defined to include emotional anxiety or psychological upset. In a criminal context, we can understand this, but let's take it out of the criminal context. For example, a Pastor, or a homeschool mom that posts things on social media against the accepted narrative, or a frustrated parent at a PTA meeting could be considered a "serious harm to the community", especially since they have been considered by some to be "domestic terrorists". As Americans, we have the Constitutionally protected rights to face our accusers, the right to a speedy trial, the right to be considered innocent until proven guilty. I cautioned Eric Toney that I was worried this was going to be like a J6 prisoner situation, where they had their rights stripped from them. 

And he immediately said, Oh, well those J6 prisoners killed police officers (basically they got what they deserved) and that he was sure they all received a speedy trial.

We were all stunned. The interactive room didn't say a word. Seriously? Eric Toney has THAT view of J6? but he is positive nothing can go wrong with a yes vote on Referendum 1.
